Data-Driven Insights into Car Valuation

1. How does engine size correlate with vehicle price across different brands?

In[9]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df = pd.read_csv("car_price_dataset.csv")
brand_stats = df.groupby('Brand').agg({'Engine_Size': 'mean', 'Price': 'mean'}).reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(brand_stats['Brand'], brand_stats['Engine_Size'], label='Avg Engine Size')
plt.bar(brand_stats['Brand'], brand_stats['Price'], alpha=0.5, label='Avg Price')
plt.xlabel('Brand')
plt.ylabel('Value')
plt.title('Engine Size vs. Price by Brand')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend()
plt.savefig("engine size vs price.png")
plt.show()

3. Relationship between Mileage, Vehicle Age, and Price

In[11]:
# Create age groups (e.g., 0-5 years, 6-10 years)
df['Age_Group'] = pd.cut(2023 - df['Year'], bins=[0, 5, 10, 20], labels=['New', 'Mid', 'Old'])

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.scatter(df['Mileage'], df['Price'], alpha=0.3)
plt.xlabel('Mileage')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.title('Mileage vs. Price')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
df.groupby('Age_Group',observed=True)['Price'].mean().plot(kind='line', marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Age Group')
plt.ylabel('Average Price')
plt.title('Price Trend by Vehicle Age')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("mileage vs price.png")
plt.show()

9. Feature Importance for Price Prediction

In[17]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

X = df[['Year', 'Mileage', 'Owner_Count']]
y = df['Price']
model = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)

importance = pd.Series(model.coef_, index=X.columns)
importance.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(8, 4))
plt.ylabel('Coefficient Magnitude')
plt.title('Feature Importance in Price Prediction')
plt.savefig(" price predition.png")
plt.show()

12. Vehicle Clusters (Luxury vs. Economy)

In[21]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

X_cluster = df[['Engine_Size', 'Price']]
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2).fit(X_cluster)
df['Cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

cluster_stats = df.groupby('Cluster')[['Engine_Size', 'Price']].mean()
cluster_stats.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(8, 4))
plt.title('Feature Averages by Cluster')
plt.savefig("luxury vs economy.png")
plt.show()

15. Regression Model Accuracy

In[25]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("car_price_dataset.csv")

# Define features (X) and target (y)
X = df[['Year', 'Mileage', 'Owner_Count']]  # Ensure these columns exist
y = df['Price']

# Train the model
model = LinearRegression()  # <-- Define the model
model.fit(X, y)             # <-- Train it on your data

# Now generate predictions
predicted = model.predict(X)

# Plot actual vs. predicted
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(y, predicted, alpha=0.3)
plt.plot([y.min(), y.max()], [y.min(), y.max()], 'r--')
plt.xlabel('Actual Price')
plt.ylabel('Predicted Price')
plt.title('Predicted vs. Actual Prices')
plt.savefig(" prediction vs actual prices.png")
plt.show()
